<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911008-0039</DOCNO><DOCID>911008-0039.</DOCID><HL>   General Dynamics' Stock   May Trigger Big Bonuses</HL><DATE>10/08/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   GD</CO><MS>TECHNOLOGY (TEC)</MS><IN>AEROSPACE (ARO)</IN><NS>MANAGEMENT ISSUES (MNT)</NS><RE>MISSOURI (MO)NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   ST. LOUIS -- Twenty-five senior executives of GeneralDynamics Corp. stand to receive bonuses equal to twice theirbase salaries if the defense contractor's stock hits at least$46.5625 today.   If it does, it will be the 10th consecutive day that thestock has been at least $10 above the $35.5625 level that itreached in May, triggering for the second time this year acontroversial executive compensation plan. William Anders,who implemented the plan after becoming chairman in January,would receive a bonus worth $1.6 million.</LP><TEXT>   General Dynamics was quoted at $47.625, down 87.5 cents,in late New York Stock Exchange trading yesterday.   Under the plan, the 25 executives last spring receivedbonuses equal to their base salaries. The bonuses wereawarded when the company's stock, for the 10th consecutiveday, was at least $10 above the $25.5625 level that it stoodat when the plan was adopted. Each subsequent $10 jump in theshare price, maintained for 10 days, calls for the executivesto get additional bonuses equal to two times their basesalaries.   The program expires in February 1994, when 50% of theawards will be made. The other half will be held until theexecutives reach age 65.</TEXT></DOC>